  "method": "We propose Cross-Judged, Compute-Aware Self-Training (C-CAST), a bootstrapping pipeline that turns model-generated outputs into training data without collapsing onto its existing mistakes. For each unlabeled input, we generate a diverse set of candidates by sampling with varied decoding parameters and using multiple checkpoints/snapshots to widen support. Each candidate is scored on a graded scale by an auxiliary reward/quality model trained with robust pairwise preference methods, and its score is further cross-checked by complementary judges (e.g., smaller models, task-specific heuristics, or an LLM verifier) to reduce single-judge bias. Rather than a binary accept/reject, candidates (and partial segments within them, when applicable) receive confidence weights; we also compute a novelty score that measures dissimilarity to the current training distribution to guard against over-concentration on frequent patterns.\n\nFrom these graded and novelty-aware signals, we construct mixed-quality pools and sample for training with probabilities proportional to a tempered function of quality times a novelty bonus. To prevent over-reliance on a small high-quality subset, we schedule the mixture over time using compute-aware filtering laws: each pool has a repetition half-life and utility parameter that decay its sampling weight as similar examples are seen repeatedly. This yields an explicit curriculum that prioritizes high-value data early but smoothly shifts mass to underused pools as their marginal utility rises, maintaining breadth. Within each minibatch, we enforce coverage by diversity-aware selection (e.g., clustering or DPP-lite subsampling) so the effective training set spans modes rather than collapsing to a few easy templates.\n\nThe model is trained with a multi-task objective: a primary supervised loss with confidence weighting from the graded scores, plus auxiliary consistency/verification losses that encode task-specific constraints or cross-view agreements. Pseudo-labels are updated online: after each epoch, we re-run the model on the unlabeled inputs and fuse these fresh predictions with stored pseudo-labels according to their respective confidences, so the supervision adapts to the learner rather than ossifying early errors. To stabilize optimization and avert reward hacking or verbosity drift, we add a trust-region KL constraint to a reference model and an entropy regularizer, and we refresh the reward/quality model periodically with a small batch of human-calibrated preferences.\n\nC-CAST runs in cycles. Each cycle regenerates candidates with exploration-friendly settings, re-scores them via the robust ensemble of judges, updates pool utilities and half-lives given the available compute budget, and retrains with the scheduled mixture. A stratified, gold-labeled validation set monitors head and tail performance; if tail metrics degrade, the next cycle allocates more generation to targeted inputs/prompts for those slices. This closed loop—graded cross-judgment, compute-aware scheduling, diversity-aware sampling, online pseudo-label refinement, and guardrails against over-optimization—bootstraps quality while preserving distributional coverage.",
  "rationale": "Distributional collapse typically arises when self-training relies on a single judge, binary thresholds, and repeated passes over a narrow high-score subset. C-CAST addresses each failure mode directly: graded scoring preserves informative partial successes, ensemble judging with a robust reward model dampens single-judge biases and reward hacking, and novelty-aware, compute-calibrated sampling limits overexposure to any pool while ensuring fresh, diverse supervision.\n\nOnline pseudo-label refinement and auxiliary consistency losses prevent early pseudo-label errors from hardening, allowing the supervision signal to track the improving model. Finally, trust-region regularization and targeted regeneration for underperforming slices provide additional safety valves against drift and mode collapse. Together, these components enable reliable self-bootstrapping that improves quality without sacrificing coverage.",
